[1]
Date: Sat 30 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AP Online, Sat 30 Nov 2002 [edited]

Uttar Pradesh: Outbreaks of Fatal Febrile Illness Affecting Children
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Health experts have begun investigating a mysterious [illness] that has
killed nearly 100 children and sickened hundreds of others over the last 2
months in India's northern state of Uttar Pradesh, officials said on Sat 30
Nov 2002. The children, mostly below 12 years of age, have died in hospitals
in small towns following what doctors and district officials said was high
fever brought on by mosquito bites.
At least 60 children have died in Saharanpur, the worst-hit district, said
Chandan L. Choudhury, the district administrator. The area is 120 miles east
of the state capital, Lucknow. Two teams of doctors and public health
specialists from the federal and state government have begun investigations
in Saharanpur to study the outbreak of the disease, said Navtej Singh,
another administrator in Saharanpur.
Children have also died in the neighboring Muzaffarnagar, Ghaziabad and
Meerut districts, he said. Doctors and government authorities were divided
over the cause of the [illness], which caused patients to show symptoms
similar to Japanese encephalitis (JE). That disease is spread from pigs to
humans through mosquito bites. It attacks the central nervous system,
causing flu-like symptoms, vomiting, paralysis and even death.
Poverty, illiteracy and a lack of hygiene lead to the death of hundreds of
children each year from diseases spread by mosquitoes and flies in Uttar
Pradesh, India's largest state in size and population. The disease had not
been widely reported by the news media as such deaths were common, local
officials said. "It's a regular phenomenon. Each year, after the rainy
season and before winter sets in, many, many children die in Uttar Pradesh.
This is nothing alarming," said Navtej Singh, the administrator. [This is a
sad state state of affairs. - Mod.JW]
[By Prajnan Bhattacharya]
