[2]
Date: Sat 30 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua News Agency (via COMTEX), Sat 30 Nov 2002 [edited]

"Mysterious" Disease Causes Death of Over 100 Children
------------------------------------------------------
Over 100 children are believed to have died due a "mysterious" disease in
Saharanpur and adjoining areas in north India's Uttar Pradesh in the past 4
to 5 days, a senior district health official said on Sat 30 Nov 2002.
However, reports quoting official sources in Lucknow put the death toll at
42.
Teams of doctors from Delhi and Lucknow have reached Saharanpur to
investigate the disease-causing agent and the nature of the disease,
Saharanpur Chief Medical Officer Ghanshyam Singh told local media. He said
that reports of deaths of children from various hospitals in the district
and neighboring areas of Baghpat district have been received and the toll
could have exceeded 100. The teams have collected blood samples, he said,
adding that the children who have succumbed to the disease are from both the
city and rural areas.
The Director General of Health Office in Lucknow said that as symptoms of
dengue, cerebral malaria and Japanese encephalitis are similar, it could not
be said that disease was encephalitis, the Press Trust of India reported.
