Date: Sat 30 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promedmail@promedmail.org>
Source: Australian Broadcasting Company News online, Sat 30 Nov 2002
[edited]
<http://abc.net.au/news/newsitems/s738244.htm>

Mystery Fever Kills 50 in North India
-------------------------------------
At least 50 children in north India have died of a mysterious fever in the
past month. A health official in the state of Uttar Pradesh says officials
do not know what disease has caused the deaths. According to local doctors,
the disease is a form of Japanese encephalitis, a deadly virus [disease]
spread by mosquitoes. The symptoms include high fever, tiredness, headache,
nausea, and vomiting.
Dr Sen, a doctor in Lucknow, says unhygienic living conditions in villages
in the districts of Saharanpur, Meerut, Baghpat and Muzzafarnagar allow the
virus to thrive. He says children are more susceptible to the disease as
their immune system was weak. [It is more likely that the adults in the area
have already survived the disease when they were children, & are immune. -
Mod.JW]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Control measures will differ depending on whether the disease is JE, dengue
or something else. Laboratory tests are available for JE, dengue & viral
encephalitides. It should be possible to make a quick diagnosis, rather
than going from year to year without knowing what diseases are striking down
children at this season. As shown below, India has difficulty in diagnosing
some diseases, and could probably use some help. - Mod.JW]
